.git/hooks/push-to-checkout.sample:
0001: #!/bin/sh
0002: 
0003: # An example hook script to update a checked-out tree on a git push.
0004: #
0005: # This hook is invoked by git-receive-pack(1) when it reacts to git
0006: # push and updates reference(s) in its repository, and when the push
0007: # tries to update the branch that is currently checked out and the
0008: # receive.denyCurrentBranch configuration variable is set to
0009: # updateInstead.
0010: #
0011: # By default, such a push is refused if the working tree and the index
0012: # of the remote repository has any difference from the currently
0013: # checked out commit; when both the working tree and the index match
0014: # the current commit, they are updated to match the newly pushed tip
0015: # of the branch. This hook is to be used to override the default
0016: # behaviour; however the code below reimplements the default behaviour
0017: # as a starting point for convenient modification.
0018: #
0019: # The hook receives the commit with which the tip of the current
0020: # branch is going to be updated:
0021: commit=$1
0022: 
0023: # It can exit with a non-zero status to refuse the push (when it does
0024: # so, it must not modify the index or the working tree).
0025: die () {
0026: 	echo >&2 "$*"
0027: 	exit 1
0028: }
0029: 
0030: # Or it can make any necessary changes to the working tree and to the
0031: # index to bring them to the desired state when the tip of the current
0032: # branch is updated to the new commit, and exit with a zero status.
0033: #
0034: # For example, the hook can simply run git read-tree -u -m HEAD "$1"
0035: # in order to emulate git fetch that is run in the reverse direction
0036: # with git push, as the two-tree form of git read-tree -u -m is
0037: # essentially the same as git switch or git checkout that switches
0038: # branches while keeping the local changes in the working tree that do
0039: # not interfere with the difference between the branches.
0040: 
0041: # The below is a more-or-less exact translation to shell of the C code
0042: # for the default behaviour for git's push-to-checkout hook defined in
0043: # the push_to_deploy() function in builtin/receive-pack.c.
0044: #
0045: # Note that the hook will be executed from the repository directory,
0046: # not from the working tree, so if you want to perform operations on
0047: # the working tree, you will have to adapt your code accordingly, e.g.
0048: # by adding "cd .." or using relative paths.
0049: 
0050: if ! git update-index -q --ignore-submodules --refresh
0051: then
0052: 	die "Up-to-date check failed"
0053: fi
0054: 
0055: if ! git diff-files --quiet --ignore-submodules --
0056: then
0057: 	die "Working directory has unstaged changes"
0058: fi
0059: 
0060: # This is a rough translation of:
0061: #
0062: #   head_has_history() ? "HEAD" : EMPTY_TREE_SHA1_HEX
0063: if git cat-file -e HEAD 2>/dev/null
0064: then
0065: 	head=HEAD
0066: else
0067: 	head=$(git hash-object -t tree --stdin </dev/null)
0068: fi
0069: 
0070: if ! git diff-index --quiet --cached --ignore-submodules $head --
0071: then
0072: 	die "Working directory has staged changes"
0073: fi
0074: 
0075: if ! git read-tree -u -m "$commit"
0076: then
0077: 	die "Could not update working tree to new HEAD"
0078: fi

